"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605929","Department of Health","false","2016-10-24","<p>Public Health England funded study by the Small Area Health Statistics Unit (SAHSU) at Imperial College and the Environmental Research Group at King’s College London investigating the potential link between emissions from municipal waste incinerators and health outcomes is ongoing. It is expected that papers from the project will be submitted by SAHSU to peer reviewed journals in spring 2017, and papers to be published later in the year.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-24T16:32:18.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605929/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605929/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605929/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","Incinerators: Health Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he expects the Health Protection Agency study on the health effects of emissions from municipal waste incinerators to be published.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","49464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605930","Department of Health","false","2016-10-24","<p>Specialised services are the responsibility of NHS England.</p><p> </p><p>The ‘Manual for Prescribed Specialised Services 2016/17’ outlines which prescribed specialised services commissioned by NHS England are related to which services commissioned by clinical commissioning groups (CCGs). It is one of a suite of products that NHS England has developed to facilitate the effective commissioning of specialised services.</p><p> </p><p>However, it does not attempt to provide a comprehensive overview of CCG commissioning responsibilities.</p><p> </p><p>The manual is available from NHS England’s website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2016/06/pss-manual-may16.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2016/06/pss-manual-may16.pdf</a></p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-10-24T10:23:00.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605930/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605930/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605930/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","Clinical Commissioning Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he has taken to make clinical commissioning groups aware of their commissioning responsibilities as set out in the manual for prescribed specialised services in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","49462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605931","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Department does not record or publish data on the nationality of staff working in the National Health Service. Data on nationality is published twice a year by NHS Digital and turnover data is published quarterly and available by nationality.</p><p> </p><p>Nationality is a data item within the National Workforce Data set used with a range of other data items to support workforce planning, analysis of staff movement and equality monitoring. It is not mandatory, but self-declared.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015 and 2016 requests for nationality data on NHS staff in England were published on the supplementary information part of the NHS Digital website, rather than as part of the routine Hospital and Community Health Services statistical publications. In 2016, following NHS Digital’s public consultation, NHS Digital now routinely publish tables showing the self-declared nationality of staff in staff groups and regions, bi-annually, together with quarterly turnover statistics which show the nationality of joiners and leavers to and from the NHS in England.</p><p> </p><p>The latest nationality data was published in March 2016 and the next set will be published in December 2016 showing the position at September 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The latest turnover data published in September 2016 covers the 12 month period to 30 June 2016.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","49495 ; 49496 ; 49497","2016-10-26T14:52:58.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605931/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605931/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605931/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","NHS: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what purpose data on the nationality of NHS staff is recorded and published.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","49494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605932","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Department does not record or publish data on the nationality of staff working in the National Health Service. Data on nationality is published twice a year by NHS Digital and turnover data is published quarterly and available by nationality.</p><p> </p><p>Nationality is a data item within the National Workforce Data set used with a range of other data items to support workforce planning, analysis of staff movement and equality monitoring. It is not mandatory, but self-declared.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015 and 2016 requests for nationality data on NHS staff in England were published on the supplementary information part of the NHS Digital website, rather than as part of the routine Hospital and Community Health Services statistical publications. In 2016, following NHS Digital’s public consultation, NHS Digital now routinely publish tables showing the self-declared nationality of staff in staff groups and regions, bi-annually, together with quarterly turnover statistics which show the nationality of joiners and leavers to and from the NHS in England.</p><p> </p><p>The latest nationality data was published in March 2016 and the next set will be published in December 2016 showing the position at September 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The latest turnover data published in September 2016 covers the 12 month period to 30 June 2016.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","49494 ; 49496 ; 49497","2016-10-26T14:52:58.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605932/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605932/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605932/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","NHS: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what changes have been made in 2016 to the level of data recorded and published on the nationality of NHS staff.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","49495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605933","Department of Health","false","2016-10-24","<p>This information is not collected by the Department.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-10-24T15:13:56.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605933/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605933/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605933/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","General Practitioners: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many GPs in England have a specialism in mental health.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","49450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605934","Department of Health","false","2016-10-24","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 12 September 2016 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=44555" target="_blank">44555</a>.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-24T13:04:14.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605934/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605934/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605934/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","General Practitioners: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many mental health workers are attached to GP practices in England.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","49449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605935","Home Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>Doctors from overseas seeking to remain in the UK are expected to meet the requirements of the Immigration Rules in the same way as any other migrant.</p><p>Should they fail to qualify to remain in the UK under the Immigration Rules they will be expected to leave the UK voluntarily but should they fail to do so then steps may be taken to enforce their departure.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-31T16:59:18.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605935/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605935/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605935/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Doctors: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy not to issue any future deportation notices to foreign-born doctors currently working in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605937","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>The table below, taken from the General Ophthalmic Services Activity Statistics for England, published by NHS Digital, shows the number of National Health Service sight tests provided to people aged 60 and over in England, between 2013/14 and 2015/16.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total NHS sight test for people aged 60 and over</p></td><td><p>% of total NHS sight tests</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>5,576,957</p></td><td><p>43.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>5,507,932</p></td><td><p>43.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>5,651,025</p></td><td><p>43.5%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>It is not possible to estimate what proportion of people eligible for free NHS sight tests used their entitlement during the reported years.</p><p> </p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><ol><li>Patients may qualify for an NHS sight test on more than one criterion. However, they would only be recorded against one criterion on the form. Patients are more likely to be recorded according to their clinical need rather than their age. For example, a patient aged over 60, with glaucoma is likely to be recorded in the glaucoma category only. The count by eligibility is therefore approximate.</li><li>The figures do not represent the number of patients, as a person may have more than one NHS sight test within the same period.</li></ol>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-10-31T09:16:17.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605937/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605937/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605937/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","Eyesight: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people in England aged over 60 had a free eye sight test in each of the last three years; and what proportion that was of the total number of people eligible for such tests.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","49328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605938","Department of Health","false","2016-10-24","<p>The following table shows the number of full-time equivalent health visitors employed in National Health Service trusts and clinical commissioning groups in England in each of the last six years. Data for July 2016 will be published by NHS Digital on 25 October 2016.</p><p> </p><p>As at 30 June each year full-time equivalent</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>7,643</p></td><td><p>7,393</p></td><td><p>8,084</p></td><td><p>8,887</p></td><td><p>10,042</p></td><td><p>9,491</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: NHS Digital NHS Hospital and Community Health Service monthly workforce statistics</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-24T12:54:05.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605938/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605938/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605938/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","Health Visitors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many full-time equivalent health visitors were employed in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","49402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605939","Department of Health","false","2016-10-27","<p>In 2017/18, as part of the wider reform of the Infected Blood Payments Scheme in England, a new discretionary scheme will replace the current three discretionary schemes. The new discretionary scheme is in design and the relationship between receipt of welfare support and eligibility for discretionary support from the new scheme has yet to be decided.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-27T10:11:06.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605939/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605939/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605939/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the reformed discretionary support scheme for people affected by contaminated blood will consider (a) housing benefit or (b) jobseeker's allowance in calculating eligibility for financial support for (i) widows and widowers of people affected and (ii) other beneficiaries.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605940","Department of Health","false","2016-10-24","<p>Yes. Local authorities who are responsible for social care will still have the flexibility in 2017-18 to raise council tax in their area by up to 2% above the existing threshold. This new funding for adult social care will be pooled with additional funding from the Better Care Fund.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-10-24T10:21:56.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605940/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605940/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605940/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether it remains Government policy to introduce a two per cent social care precept on council tax and additional funding for the Better Care Fund in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","49357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605941","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Mandate to NHS England, which sets the Government’s objectives for the provision of health services in England and any requirements for NHS England, includes an objective calling for the offer of meaningful choice in the National Health Service. This reflects the commitment in the Five Year Forward View. An assessment of the extent to which the Mandate objectives have been met is set out in my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State’s Annual Assessment of NHS England, which is published at the end of the financial year.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-26T09:26:05.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605941/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605941/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605941/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","Patient Choice Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment the Government has made of the progress in implementing the commitment in the NHS Five Year Forward View to increase patient choice over where and how patients receive care; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","49351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605942","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>No assessment has been made. Decisions about whether to use independent sector capacity are generally made at local level. Use of the independent sector will depend on a range of factors including the needs of individual local health systems, patient choice and availability of suitable independent sector capacity.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-26T09:25:04.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605942/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605942/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605942/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","NHS: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of how much additional surgical and diagnostic capacity independent sector healthcare organisations are able to make available to NHS patients over the remainder of 2016-17; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","49352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605943","Department of Health","false","2016-10-27","<p>We will continue to encourage long term partnerships between the National Health Service and the private sector in order to deliver responsive and innovative healthcare services while ensuring better value for taxpayers. It is right that these decisions are made locally by the NHS and not politicians. We are clear that patients should be able to access the best possible providers based on quality not the sector.</p><p> </p><p>Commissioners can use a range of tools to secure services, including managing providers’ performance, extending and varying contracts, widening choice of qualified provider, and tendering. They will need to choose the right tools for different circumstances. Local conditions vary and there is no one-size-fits-all model for raising standards.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-27T09:16:27.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605943/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605943/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605943/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","NHS: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment the Government has made of its progress in implementing the commitment in the 2015 Spending Review to encourage long-term partnerships between the NHS and the private sector; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","49353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605944","Department of Health","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Department has made no allocations to the Troubled Families programme over the three years 2016-17, 2017-18, and 2018-19. Government funding for this programme is through Cabinet Office.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-24T16:28:58.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605944/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605944/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605944/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","Department of Health: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what funding his Department has allocated to the Troubled Families programme for (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18 and (c) 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","49377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605945","Department of Health","false","2016-10-24","<p>Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STPs) are developed collaboratively by local organisations and partners and therefore this information is not held centrally. Meetings of the STP involved representatives from local partners across the footprint.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-10-24T13:03:22.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605945/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605945/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605945/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","Health Services: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many meetings have taken place in the Cheshire and Merseyside footprint area to discuss sustainability and transformation plans; and who attended those meetings.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","49399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605946","Department for Education","false","2016-10-27","<p>We do not hold information on those schools that do not have an automated external defibrillator on schools grounds, as the purchasing of a defibrillator is a matter for individual head teachers.</p><p> </p><p>However, we know how important swift access to a defibrillator can be in cases of cardiac arrest, which is why the Government is encouraging schools and other eligible settings to purchase a defibrillator as part of their first-aid equipment.</p><p> </p><p>To make it as easy as possible for schools to do so, the Department has negotiated a deal with NHS Supply Chain to offer defibrillators to schools at a reduced cost. Since the scheme was launched in November 2014, 1659 defibrillators have been purchased through this route.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-10-27T16:18:32.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605946/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605946/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605946/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-19","Schools: Defibrillators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number schools in England and Wales which do not have an automated external defibrillator located on school grounds; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605947","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>No estimate has been made of the number of public-access defibrillators located in Coventry, the West Midlands and England or of the number of people who have taken part in coronary pulmonary resuscitation training delivered by the National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that better provision of defibrillators and increasing the number of people trained in cardiopulmonary resuscitation could help save more lives of those who have a cardiac arrest outside a hospital setting.</p><p> </p><p>That is why the Chancellor announced in the budget in March that the Government is making available another £1 million to make public access defibrillators and coronary pulmonary resuscitation training more widely available in communities across England. This builds on last year’s funding of £1 million, which provided almost 700 more publicly accessible defibrillators in communities across England and increased the numbers of people trained in cardiopulmonary resuscitation.</p><p> </p><p>Details on how this second tranche of the funding can be accessed will be available in due course.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","49423","2016-10-26T11:03:15.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605947/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605947/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-19","First Aid: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of people who have taken part in NHS-delivered coronary pulmonary resuscitation training in the last year for which data is available; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605948","Home Office","false","2016-11-02","<p>On 12 March 2015 the former Home Secretary established the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse under the Inquiries Act 2005. The Inquiry is independent of the Government and is responsible for the management of its own budget and the publication of its own financial reports.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-02T18:03:11.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605948/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605948/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605948/answer/previousversion/16053","Biography information for Sarah Newton","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much was spent on work by Ben Emmerson QC during the period that he served as the most senior lawyer for the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse; and if she will publish a breakdown of those costs.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","49455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605949","Home Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>The flood impacted 501 immigration applications. All customers impacted were advised that their individual application was involved in the incident. Once the impact of the flood had been dealt with the applications were handled under our normal casework procedures and checks. To date 468 of the applications have been completed. The remaining 33 applications are still under consideration.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-26T15:17:31.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605949/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605949/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605949/answer/previousversion/16040","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Immigration: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many immigration applications were affected by the flooding incident at Leeds Royal Mail Depot on 15 December 2015; how many such applications have been resolved; what additional resources are being applied to resolve outstanding such cases; what the target timescales for completion of outstanding such cases are; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","49376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605950","Home Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Home Office annually publishes statistics on football banning orders imposed in England and Wales. The table below contains published statistics for the last five football seasons, detailing the total number of extant football banning orders and the number of new football banning orders imposed. A football banning order imposed in England and Wales prevents the individual from attending all matches in the Premier League and Football League. The statistics for season 2015-16 will be published on 24 November. Please refer to the table attached for detailed statistics.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-01T14:08:47.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605950/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605950/answer","PQ 49319 football banning orders-Table.doc","Football banning orders, England and Wales","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605950/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605950/answer/previousversion/16042","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Football: Hooliganism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have been banned from attending Premiership and Championship matches in England over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","49319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605951","Home Office","false","2016-11-15","<p>The Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse was established under the Inquiries Act 2005 on 12 March 2015. Dame Lowell resigned as chair of the Inquiry on 4 August 2016. Ben Emmerson QC resigned as counsel to the Inquiry on 29 September 2016.</p><p>The Home Secretary has received no correspondence from Counsel to the Inquiry relating to the conduct of either Dame Lowell or Mr Emmerson between the dates of their appointment to the Inquiry and the dates of their departure.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-15T16:49:51.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605951/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605951/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605951/answer/previousversion/16047","Biography information for Sarah Newton","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what correspondence she has received from legal counsel for the independent investigation into child sexual abuse relating to the conduct of (a) Dame Lowell Goddard and (b) Ben Emmerson QC between the date of their appointment to the inquiry and the dates of their departure.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","49322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605952","Home Office","false","2016-11-15","<p>The Home Secretary has not met the Secretary to the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse.</p><p>Home Office officials meet regularly with the Secretary to the Inquiry as part of the sponsorship responsibilities.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-15T16:54:34.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605952/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605952/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605952/answer/previousversion/16048","Biography information for Sarah Newton","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when (a) she and (b) her Department's officials have met John O'Brien, Secretary of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse since his appointment to that position.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","49323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605953","Home Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner has a remit to encourage good practice in the prevention, detection, investigation and prosecution of modern slavery offences and in the identification of victims.</p><p>This can include encouraging good practice among businesses. It is for the Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner to determine how to carry out this work.</p><p>He made ‘private sector engagement to encourage supply chain transparency’ one of his five priorities in his Strategic Plan for 2015-2017 and reported on progress in his first annual report, which was published on 12 October.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-27T17:34:18.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605953/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605953/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605953/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether it is the practice of the Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner to analyse the supply chain statements of private companies in relation to modern slavery and human trafficking.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605954","Home Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government has not estimated what proportion of businesses have reported so far.</p><p>We published guidance in October 2015 advising that businesses should report as soon as reasonably practicable after their financial year end, which in practice should mean within six months of an organisation’s financial year end.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-27T17:36:40.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605954/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605954/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the proportion of companies which have published details of the measures they are taking to eradicate slavery and human trafficking from their supply chains.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605955","Home Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>All potential victims of modern slavery receive intensive and specialist support for a minimum of 45 days, plus a further 14 days if they are conclusively found to be a victim to assist with their return home, their reintegration into society or their transfer to mainstream support.</p><p>This level of support means that the UK is exceeding its obligations under Article 12 of the European Convention on Action Against Trafficking in Human Beings (ECAT). The Government is piloting changes to aspects of the National Referral Mechanism and we will consider whether changes to existing arrangements are needed once the pilot has been evaluated.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-27T17:40:33.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605955/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605955/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government plans to extend the time period for a Conclusive Grounds Decision in the National Referral Mechanism from 45 to 90 days.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605957","Home Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>Dame Louise Casey’s independent review on boosting opportunity and integration in isolated and vulnerable communities will report to the Prime Minister and be published in due course.</p><p>The Government’s response will be a decision for the Prime Minister.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-27T16:19:00.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605957/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605957/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Community Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of Dame Louise Casey's review; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","49341"
