"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605961","Home Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Home Secretary's statement on Calais on 24 October (Column 55) referred to the proper safeguarding, age assessment and security checks we carry out, working closely with local authorities and social workers in the UK, to ensure that the children transferred here are eligible to come and it is in their best interests to do so.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-08T17:13:35.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605961/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605961/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605961/answer/previousversion/16092","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Children: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether it is her policy to undertake tooth checks for incoming unaccompanied child refugees.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","49457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605962","Home Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>Serco are considering the acquisition of their sub contractor in Scotland and Northern Ireland region and are undertaking analysis of all pertinent matters. The due diligence activity is a matter for Serco.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-26T15:15:50.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605962/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605962/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605962/answer/previousversion/16089","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Compass contract in Scotland with Serco for asylum accommodation and the press notice issued by Serco on 21 September 2016, Compass contract in Scotland and Northern Ireland, which headings will be covered in the due diligence process.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","49447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605963","Home Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>No such allegations have ever been raised with the Home Secretary.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-03T17:28:59.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605963/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605963/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605963/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605963/answer/previousversion/16075","Biography information for Sarah Newton","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on what date she first became aware that allegations of racism had been made against Dame Lowell Goddard in her capacity as Chair of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse; and who made her aware of those allegations.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","49466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605964","Home Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Home Office has not allocated funding for the Troubled Families programme for 2016-17, 2017-18 or 2018-19.</p><p>From 2016/17 onwards, HM Treasury has baselined funding of the Troubled Families programme so it is deducted before Departments receive their allocations to avoid the need for the Department for Communities and Local Government (DCLG) to approach Departments individually to ask for contributions.</p><p>Therefore, the Home Office no longer provides funding directly to DCLG for the Troubled Families programme.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-27T15:46:55.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605964/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605964/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605964/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Home Office: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has allocated funds for the Troubled Families programme for (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18 and (c) 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","49433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605965","Home Office","false","2016-11-02","<p>On 12 March 2015 the former Home Secretary established the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse under the Inquiries Act 2005. The Inquiry is independent of the Government and is responsible for the management of its own budget and the publication of its own financial reports.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-02T18:03:30.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605965/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605965/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605965/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605965/answer/previousversion/16059","Biography information for Sarah Newton","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what expenses were claimed by Dame Lowell Goddard during her time as Chair of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse; and if she will publish a breakdown of those expenses.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","49458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605966","Home Office","false","2016-11-16","<p>The Home Office has deployed teams of officials to work alongside French officials in Calais to assist with speeding up the Dublin process and to identify and prioritise children who will be brought to the UK under the terms of the Dubs amendment to the Immigration Act 2016. Staff have been deployed flexibly to meet demand on the ground. We have also seconded an expert on Dublin cases to the French Interior Ministry – the second time we have done so this year.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-16T17:32:54.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605966/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605966/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605966/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Asylum: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the oral contribution by the Home Secretary of 10 October 2016, Official Report, column 38, if she will write to the hon. Member for Kingston upon Hull North about reports that her Department has announced the doubling of asylum experts in France working on the Calais cases.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605967","Home Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>Liz Sanderson was the then Home Secretary’s special adviser. The Department holds no records of separate meetings or conversations between Ms Sanderson and Dame Lowell Goddard, panel members or the statutory officers. However, she routinely attended the Home Secretary’s meetings, including with Dame Lowell Goddard and panel members during the appointment processes. She also had occasional conversations with the Secretary to the Inquiry.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","49521 ; 49522","2016-12-02T14:11:03.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605967/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605967/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605967/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many meetings took place between Liz Sanderson and the Secretary of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse, John O'Brien; on what dates those meetings took place; and who was present at each such meeting.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","49520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605968","Home Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>Liz Sanderson was the then Home Secretary’s special adviser. The Department holds no records of separate meetings or conversations between Ms Sanderson and Dame Lowell Goddard, panel members or the statutory officers. However, she routinely attended the Home Secretary’s meetings, including with Dame Lowell Goddard and panel members during the appointment processes. She also had occasional conversations with the Secretary to the Inquiry.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","49520 ; 49522","2016-12-02T14:11:04.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605968/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605968/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many meetings took place between Liz Sanderson and members of the panel of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse; on what dates those meetings took place; and who was present at each such meeting.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","49521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605969","Home Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>Liz Sanderson was the then Home Secretary’s special adviser. The Department holds no records of separate meetings or conversations between Ms Sanderson and Dame Lowell Goddard, panel members or the statutory officers. However, she routinely attended the Home Secretary’s meetings, including with Dame Lowell Goddard and panel members during the appointment processes. She also had occasional conversations with the Secretary to the Inquiry.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","49520 ; 49521","2016-12-02T14:11:04.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605969/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605969/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605969/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many meetings were held between Dame Lowell Goddard and Liz Sanderson in connection with the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse; who was present at each such meeting; and if she publish the minutes of those meetings.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","49522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605970","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-24","<p>There are no plans currently to allow the road rescue industry to use red lights when recovering broken down vehicles. There are a range of existing measures available to make rescue vehicles visible and warn others of their presence such as the use of roof mounted amber beacons and retro-reflective material to the side and rear.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-24T16:32:53.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605970/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605970/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","Breakdown Vehicles: Lighting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans the Government has to allow the road rescue industry to use red lights when recovering broken down vehicles.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","49546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605972","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-25","<p>Eradicating extreme poverty by 2030 is the primary purpose of UK aid under the International Development Act and one of the UK Aid Strategy’s objectives. DFID’s 2015/16 Annual Report sets out progress against our Single Departmental Plan, and hence to delivery of the 2030 Agenda. Progress in 2016/17 will be set out in our next Annual Report.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-10-25T15:27:56.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605972/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605972/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605972/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-19","Developing Countries: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what contribution her Department has made to UN Sustainable Development Goal 1 on poverty eradication in the last six months; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","49507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605973","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-24","<p>The UN High Commissioner for Refugees assesses that there are an estimated 9,155 people living in the al-Hol refugee camp, including 5,650 Iraqi refugees; and shortages of food, water and health services. DFID funds World Food Programme and UNICEF’s 2016 Syria appeals through which we are supporting the provision of food, water, sanitation and hygiene services in the camp. DFID is also supporting an international non-governmental organisation to provide protection services in the camp.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-24T15:42:05.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605973/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605973/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605973/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-19","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the humanitarian situation in the al-Hol refugee camp in Syria; and what steps her Department is taking to support refugees within that camp.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","49461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605974","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-25","<p>Survey data on infant and child mortality rates shows that mortality rates are much higher in the north of Nigeria compared to the south.</p><p>In 2015/16, of a total DFID bilateral spend in Nigeria of £214m, approximately 60% of programming focused in six northern states. Additionally, over the last two years, DFID has scaled up its response to the ongoing humanitarian crisis in the northeast, bringing life-saving support to those affected by the Boko Haram insurgency.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-10-25T15:26:04.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605974/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605974/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605974/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-19","Nigeria: Life Expectancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what representations she has received on trends in life expectancy in Northern Nigeria; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","49505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605975","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-25","<p>The UK is the fourth largest donor to Yemen with an additional £37 million in UK funding for Yemen announced at the UN General Assembly. This brings the UK’s total to £100 million in humanitarian assistance for 2016/17 which is provided to aid organisations in Yemen. Last year, we helped more than 1.3 million Yemenis with food, medical supplies, water, and emergency shelter.</p><p>We also continue to urge parties to the conflict to take all reasonable steps to facilitate rapid, safe and unhindered humanitarian access to ensure our partners are able to deliver aid to its intended beneficiaries.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-10-25T15:27:08.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605975/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605975/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605975/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-19","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department is giving to aid organisations based in Yemen to deliver humanitarian assistance in that country.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","49506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605976","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-24","<p>​(i) The total allocation for 2016-17 for both Israel and the OPTs is £7m. It is not separated into individual, distinct budgets as some of our projects and implementing partners deliver simultaneously in both (a) and (b).</p><p>(ii) We do not yet have a projected budget for 2017-18 so cannot provide this information.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-24T16:19:36.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605976/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605976/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605976/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-19","Middle East: Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the budget is for projects in (a) Israel and (b) the Palestinian territories within the Conflict, Security and Stability Fund (i) in 2016-17 and (ii) as projected for 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","49492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605978","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-24","<p>The following projects are funded from the Conflict, Security and Stability Fund (CSSF) during the current financial year (2016/17). These are projected spend figures and so are subject to change.</p><p>- Small training team as part of the United States Security Coordinator to provide institutional development and professionalisation of the Palestinian Authority Security Forces. £2.23m.</p><p>- Technical assistance to the Palestinian Ministry of Interior (MOI) to improve its capability to provide oversight and management of the security services. £1.8m.</p><p>- Support to EU Coordinating Office for Palestinian Police Support. £0.067m.</p><p>- Empowerment of young Israeli leaders to strengthen support for peace in their communities. £0.3m.</p><p>- UK-Israel Informal Security Dialogue. £0.025m.</p><p>- Legal Aid and Settlement Monitoring in the West Bank. £1.5m.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-24T16:25:48.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605978/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605978/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605978/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-19","Middle East: Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which projects in Israel and the Palestinian territories were supported from the Conflict, Security and Stability Fund in 2016-17; and what the level of funding and support was for each such project.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","49493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605979","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-26","<p>The UK aims to reduce Afghanistan’s dependence on aid and help make it a more prosperous safe and stable country.</p><p>The UK supports the extractives sector to accelerate economic development and revenue generation. Through the £10.3m Extractive Sector Support Programme, the UK has recommended revisions to the Minerals Law and provided support for the Ministry of Mines and Petroleum to incorporate amendments.</p><p>The Mining Advisory Council is currently reviewing the amendments. Following this review, the amendments will go to the Ministry of Justice, the Council of Ministers, Parliament and finally the President for enactment. The UK remains committed to working closely with the Government and other stakeholders in support of this process.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-26T16:11:24.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605979/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605979/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605979/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-19","Afghanistan: Mining","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what (a) technical support her Department has offered and (b) political engagement with the Afghan government her Department plans in order to ensure that the Afghan government fulfils the commitment it made at the Brussels Conference on Afghanistan, held on 4-5 October 2016, on amendments to the mining law; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","49419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605980","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-24","<p>Statistics for assaults on staff by prison are available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-june-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-june-2016</a></p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-24T16:39:51.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605980/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605980/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605980/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-19","Risley Prison: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many incidents of violence against prison staff at HMP Risley have been recorded in each year from 2010 to the latest date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","49400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605981","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-24","<p>There is no MoJ funding allocated to the Troubled Families programme for (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18 and (c) 2018-19.</p><p> </p><p>MOJ works with DCLG to encourage Troubled Families teams to co-operate with offender management services to identify families for the programme. MoJ is also supporting the evaluation of the programme through data matching with administrative data sets such as the Police National Computer.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-24T16:50:22.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605981/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605981/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605981/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-19","Ministry of Justice: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what funding her Department has allocated to the Troubled Families programme for (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18 and (c) 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","49378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605982","Attorney General","false","2016-10-25","<p>In 2015-16 the CPS conviction rate in rape cases rose to 57.9% from 56.9% in 2014-15. The volumes of convictions reached 2,689. This is the highest volume ever recorded and represents a rise of 108 defendants (4.2%) since 2014-15.</p><p> </p><p>The CPS continues to prioritise its response to cases involving allegations of rape and other forms of serious sexual offending and has taken a number of steps to improve the conviction rate. These include increasing the number of specialist staff within its dedicated Rape and Serious Sexual Offences (RASSO) Units; providing revised and up-dated specialist training for prosecutors, and developing closer working arrangements with the police, including enhanced arrangements for the provision of early investigative advice to assist the police to build stronger cases.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-10-25T10:04:48.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605982/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605982/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605982/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-10-19","Rape: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the recent change in the proportion of rape cases that result in a conviction; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","49401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605983","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-24","<p>Information on the number of prison officers employed and on the prison population are available on gov.uk. The published workforce information covers public sector prisons only and so is not directly comparable to the headline population information.</p><p> </p><p>Safe prisons are fundamental to the proper functioning of our justice system. Our dedicated prison officers, who support tens of thousands of prisoners every day, are vital to the safe running of our prisons. We have recruited 2,900 staff over the last 12 months and are taking significant action to make sure we have appropriate staffing levels.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-24T16:39:32.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605983/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605983/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605983/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-19","Prison Officers: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many full-time equivalent prison officers there were in England and Wales; and what the ratio of prison officers to prisoners was in prisons in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","49558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605984","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>The honourable Lady highlighted the work carried out in her constituency by North Down Alternatives during a recent Northern Ireland Affairs Committee evidence session. Following that debate I asked my officials to make arrangements for me to meet the accredited restorative justice groups that co-operate with the police in Northern Ireland.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-10-31T15:44:46.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605984/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605984/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605984/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-19","Reparation by Offenders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what plans he has to meet representatives of restorative justice schemes in Northern Ireland; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","49364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605986","Prime Minister","false","2016-10-24","<p>I refer the Hon member to the answer that I gave her on Wednesday 19 October, Official Report, column 801.</p><p> </p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-10-24T12:04:03.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605986/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605986/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605986/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-10-19","Lowell Goddard","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, on what date she first became aware that allegations of misconduct had been made against Dame Lowell Goddard in her capacity as Chair of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse; what those allegations were; and who made her aware of those allegations.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","49467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605987","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) ensures compliance with the cabotage regulations by carrying out roadside checks, which are conducted by DVSA enforcement examiners.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-24T16:01:59.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605987/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605987/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605987/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","Cabotage: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what system is available to the Driver Vehicle Standards Agency to ensure compliance with cabotage regulations.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","49470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605988","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-26","<p>A permanent Construction Commissioner will be appointed following Royal Assent of the High Speed Rail (London to West Midlands) Bill.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-26T13:53:53.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605988/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605988/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605988/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","High Speed Two: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects a permanent High Speed 2 Construction Commissioner to be appointed.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605989","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-24","<p>We anticipate the Community and Environment, and Business and Local Economy funds will be open for applications in early 2017 at which point guidance on the application process will be published.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-24T16:08:24.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605989/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605989/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605989/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how and when the Community and Environment Fund and Business and Local Economy Fund allocated to the route of High Speed 2 Phase One will become available.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605990","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Secretary of State will consider and approve proposals for membership of the independent panel following Royal Assent of the High Speed Rail (London to West Midlands) Bill.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-24T16:18:31.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605990/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605990/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605990/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when it is planned that the independent regulatory body to whom the High Speed 2 Interim Construction Commissioner will report and be held accountable will be appointed; who will make up that body; and who will decide who is appointed to that body.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605991","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-24","<p>McLean Partnership have provided two forms of service to date; executive search at a cost of £588,750, and provision of administrative and payroll services for interim staff at a cost of £286,306.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-24T16:22:54.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605991/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605991/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605991/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","High Speed Two","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what services are being provided to HS2 Ltd by the Maclean Partnership; and what the cost of those services has been to date.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605992","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-24","<p>The salary of the Interim HS2 Construction Commissioner is £575 per day, plus VAT. Correspondence to the Interim Commissioner can be addressed to HS2 Ltd, 1 Canada Square, London, E14 5AB or by email to <a href="mailto:complaints@hs2-cc.org.uk" target="_blank">complaints@hs2-cc.org.uk</a>. The Interim Commissioner can also be contacted via the following website: <a href="https://hs2cc.wordpress.com/contact/" target="_blank">https://hs2cc.wordpress.com/contact/</a>.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-24T16:29:59.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605992/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605992/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605992/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","High Speed Two","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the (a) salary, (b) postal address and (c) other contact details are of the interim Construction Commissioner for High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605993","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-27","<p>A) Airports</p><p> </p><p>Under international treaties administered by the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO), all contracting states are responsible for the implementation of aviation security regimes in their own airports, to be applied according to a number of standards and recommended practices set out by ICAO.</p><p> </p><p>However, implementation of these aviation security standards around the world does vary and can be less effective when compared to those in the UK. The Department for Transport therefore works closely with a wide range of overseas governments to first assess their implementation and then assist them where necessary, to build their capacity and strengthen their aviation security, governance and procedures. We also work closely with airlines to implement additional security measures, where judged appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>B) Ports</p><p> </p><p>Under the International Ship and Port Facility Security (ISPS) Code it is the responsibility of the host state to implement effective security measures at their ports in accordance with the ISPS Code and based on that state’s assessment of the maritime security risks. The UK takes maritime security extremely seriously, and the Department has recently established an International Maritime Security Engagement programme to assess security standards at key foreign ports and to provide training in UK best practice to help raise standards.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-27T14:15:34.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605993/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605993/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605993/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what measures his Department uses to assess the effectiveness of security at (a) airports and (b) ports of other countries offering connections to the UK.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","49408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605994","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-27","<p>Under international treaties administered by the International Civil Aviation Organisation (ICAO), all contracting states are responsible for the implementation of aviation security regimes in their own airports, to be applied according to a number of standards and recommended practices set out by ICAO.</p><p> </p><p>Baggage belonging to air passengers arriving in the UK is screened for security purposes at the airport of departure and would only be re-screened if the passenger was taking an onward flight from a UK airport.</p><p> </p><p>The standards of aviation security applied to flights inbound to the UK are a priority for the Department for Transport. The Department deploys a network of skilled professionals to engage with host states supporting the improvement of standards in aviation security. This is to ensure the protection of all inbound UK flights, out of those regions by identifying and mitigating security risks, including vulnerabilities at international airports worldwide.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-27T14:20:22.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605994/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605994/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605994/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","Aviation: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what processes the Government has in place to check luggage on flights to the UK at (a) departing airports with known security concerns and (b) the destination airport.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","49409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605995","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-27","<p>Information on the amount lost by businesses in Birmingham and the West Midlands conurbation as a result of congestion on the M6 motorway is not held centrally.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-27T14:51:45.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605995/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605995/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605995/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","M6: Road Traffic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will estimate the amount lost by businesses in Birmingham and the West Midlands conurbation as a result of congestion on the M6 motorway in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Khalid Mahmood","Birmingham, Perry Barr","Mr Khalid Mahmood","49317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605997","Women and Equalities","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Government is considering different options for celebrating and supporting pride events in 2017 and will provide further details in due course.</p><p> </p><p>At Pride this year, the Government demonstrated its commitment to LGB&amp;T equality in different ways: we flew the rainbow flag on top of the government buildings; the Prime Minister Theresa May issued a statement of solidarity with the LGB&amp;T community ahead of the Brighton Pride, and I released an op-ed ahead of the Portsmouth Pride.</p><p> </p><p>We are looking forward to celebrating the diversity of our communities at Pride next year.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-02T17:58:54.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605997/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605997/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605997/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-10-19","LGBT People: Kingston upon Hull","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what support the Government plans to provide to Hull for the national LGBT+ Pride festival in 2017; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605998","Women and Equalities","false","2016-11-02","<p>Tackling the gender pay gap is an absolute priority for this Government. We will lay regulations requiring large employers to publish the difference between the average earnings of their male and female employees at the earliest opportunity. Our consultation on how gender pay gap reporting will be extended to public sector organisations closed on 30 September and we are currently analysing responses.</p><p>We are making sure that women are given the opportunity to progress from the classroom to the boardroom. As well as encouraging girls to consider a range of careers through the ‘Your Life’ campaign, we have extended the right to request flexible working to all employees; introduced a new system of flexible parental leave; and committed to providing 30 hours of free childcare a week for working families. Nearly two-thirds of the people benefitting from the National Living Wage are women.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-02T17:59:42.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605998/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605998/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-10-19","Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps she is taking to reduce the gender pay gap.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","49499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605999","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Green Paper will explore a range of ways to improve the prospects and transform the lives of disabled people and people with musculoskeletal conditions and other long term health conditions so that their health needs and employment aspirations are met in the best possible way.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-24T11:20:55.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605999/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605999/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605999/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will take steps to include proposals related to musculoskeletal conditions in the planned Green Paper on disability employment.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","49480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606000","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-24","<p>We are currently reviewing the timetable for the closure of Child Support Agency arrears only cases.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-10-24T15:59:59.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606000/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606000/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606000/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 12 June 2016 to Question 42169, what his Department's timetable is for the closure of remaining arrears-only Child Support Agency cases after the current three year programme for closing cases with an ongoing liability is completed.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","49485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606001","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-24","<p>The closure of existing child maintenance cases on the 1993 and 2003 schemes is proceeding as planned. The timetable for the closure of the underlying 1993 and 2003 child support IT systems is currently under consideration.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-10-24T16:23:21.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606001/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606001/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Child Support Agency: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's proposed deadline is for closing the 1993 and 2003 Child Support Agency IT system.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","49471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606002","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-24","<p>We have interpreted this question to mean “how Child Support Agency (CSA) (a) clients and (b) former clients <strong>actively</strong> request collection of any CSA arrears held by the Child Maintenance Service.” If a client or former client of the Child Support Agency (CSA) would like their arrears collected they should call the Child Maintenance Service (CMS). When debt is moved from the Child Support Agency to the Child Maintenance Service system, clients receive a letter that includes contact details for the CMS.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-10-24T16:02:17.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606002/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606002/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 14 June 2016 to Question 40130, how Child Support Agency (CSA) (a) client and (b) former client activity requests collection of any CSA arrears held by the Child Maintenance Service.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","49484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606003","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-24","<p>The arrears cleansing process is a feature of the case closure programme, and cases selected for closure will be subject to arrears cleanse before the debt is moved to the Child Maintenance Service system. Cases are not subject to the arrears cleanse process unless they are selected for closure.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-10-24T16:16:20.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606003/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606003/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure that arrears-only Child Support Agency  cases outside the current pro-active case-closure programme will be subject to the arrears cleansing process before being transferred to the Child Maintenance Service for collection.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","49472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606004","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-24","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 20 October 2016 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-10-17/48978/" target="_blank">UIN 48978</a>.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-24T11:38:40.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606004/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606004/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Employment and Support Allowance: Chronic Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which chronic illnesses and severe conditions exempt employment and support allowance claimants from regular medical reassessments.","false","Biography information for Dr Alasdair McDonnell","Belfast South","Dr Alasdair McDonnell","49460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606005","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>The information available for the number of Jobseeker’s Allowance claimants by Parliamentary Constituency and duration is published and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp</a></p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-26T11:05:24.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606005/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606005/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Jobseeker's Allowance: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants in each constituency in Scotland have been in receipt of jobseeker's allowance for (a) one year, (b) two years and (c) five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Eilidh Whiteford","Banff and Buchan","Dr Eilidh Whiteford","49435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606006","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-24","<p>The information is not available and can only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-24T15:00:47.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606006/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606006/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606006/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Social Security Benefits: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the time advisors from the Citizens Advice Bureau are placed on hold while making enquiries on behalf of clients for (a) employment and support allowance and (b) personal independence payments claims.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","49325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606007","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>The length of a Personal Independence Payment (PIP) award is based on an individual’s circumstances and can vary from 9 months to an on-going award with a light touch review at the ten year point. PIP already recognises that for the most severely disabled claimants, the award review process could seem unnecessarily intrusive. Existing PIP claimants with the most severe, lifetime disabilities, whose functional ability has remained the same, are more likely to have their evidence reviewed by a DWP Decision Maker and will not need to have another face-to-face assessment with a healthcare professional.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-26T14:29:20.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606007/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606007/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606007/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Personal Independence Payment: Chronic Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will take steps to end reassessments for personal independence payments claimants with lifelong or degenerative conditions in line with his Department's policy on employment and support allowance.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","49342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606008","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>We will be working over the coming months with medical professionals and other stakeholders to develop a process and functional criteria that will help us identify those with the most severe health conditions or disabilities, for whom repeat work capability assessments can be stopped. This change will only apply to those placed in the Support Group and Universal Credit equivalent.</p><p>No proportion of Support Group claimants can be estimated until the criteria has been agreed. This change will come into effect by the end of 2017.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","49345","2016-10-26T13:18:32.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606008/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606008/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606008/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to his Written Ministerial Statement of 10 October 2016, HCWS174, what steps his Department plans to take to ensure that relevant employment and support allowance claimants are not reassessed unnecessarily.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606009","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>We will be working over the coming months with medical professionals and other stakeholders to develop a process and functional criteria that will help us identify those with the most severe health conditions or disabilities, for whom repeat work capability assessments can be stopped. This change will only apply to those placed in the Support Group and Universal Credit equivalent.</p><p>No proportion of Support Group claimants can be estimated until the criteria has been agreed. This change will come into effect by the end of 2017.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","49346","2016-10-26T13:18:32.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606009/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606009/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606009/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to his Written Ministerial Statement of 10 October 2016, HCWS174, what proportion of existing (a) support and (b) work related-activity group claimants of employment and support allowance will (i) continue and (ii) cease to be subject to re-assessment.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606010","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Department has teams of performance managers who work with providers to ensure they keep to their contracted obligations, which include an understanding of the demands of their local labour market and consideration of disabled applicants.</p><p>There are specific programmes which support disabled people with entering or retaining work, and through which providers can work with local employers. These include Work Programme, Work Choice, and Specialist Employability Support.</p><p>Additionally, Disability Confident was launched in July 2013. Disability Confident supports this Government’s commitment to halve the employment gap between disabled and non-disabled people by focusing on the role of employers, who have a crucial role to play in ensuring disabled people are recruited, retained and developed in their careers. When employers sign up as Disability Confident, they are asked to make specific meaningful offers of opportunities for disabled people such as jobs, apprenticeships, internships, and work experience opportunities. So far, over 1900 businesses have signed up to the new Disability Confident scheme, with this number growing daily.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-26T11:19:41.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606010/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606010/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606010/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that providers of his Department's services (a) better understand the demands of the local labour market and (b) reach out to employers to encourage them to consider disabled applicants.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","49350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606011","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions has not allocated direct funding to the Troubled Families Programme in those financial years. The Department has allocated funding for around 300 Troubled Families Employment Advisors to drive improved employment outcomes.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-26T15:04:43.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606011/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606011/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606011/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Department for Work and Pensions: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what funding his Department has allocated to the Troubled Families Programme for (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18 and (c) 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","49367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606012","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy is currently working closely with the Department for Exiting the EU to understand the impacts that withdrawal from the EU will have on businesses, consumers and other economic actors. As my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister has said, we will work hard to get the best deal for Britain.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-26T10:01:59.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606012/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606012/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606012/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Non-tariff Barriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to protect UK industry from non-tariff barriers in the event of the UK leaving the single market.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","49380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606013","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-25","<p>The attached table sets out the number of applications for new Development Consent Orders (“DCO”) for energy infrastructure projects which the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and the former Department of Energy and Climate Change considered in each year since the Planning Act 2008 system for nationally significant infrastructure projects came into force on 1 March 2010. The year given is the year when the decision was made. The region given is the region in which the Planning Inspectorate classifies the project.</p><p>The former Infrastructure Planning Commission made one decision to grant an energy infrastructure DCO before its abolition (2011 – East of England, not included in the table).</p><p>One application was originally refused consent before being granted consent on redetermination. That is included as a grant of consent only in the table.</p><p>The Department is currently considering one application for a DCO (not included in the attached table).</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-25T10:29:01.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606013/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606013/answer","WPQ 49349 Table.docx","New energy infrastructure DCOs","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606013/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Development Consent Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many Development Consent Orders for energy projects his Department considered in each region in each year since 2009-10; and how many such Orders were (a) accepted and (b) rejected.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606014","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Government supports the development of new interconnection where it delivers benefits to the consumer, and our approach is designed to deliver those benefits in the most efficient way. We have a developer-led approach to interconnection where the market identifies the best projects and applies to Ofgem to assess their merits. In the 2016 Budget the Government said that it supports the increase of interconnection capacity to at least 9GW; if a developer was to propose additional capacity between Northern Ireland and the GB market, Ofgem would assess it on its merits.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-25T08:40:06.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606014/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606014/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606014/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Electricity Interconnectors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the merits of increasing the capacity of the Moyle electricity interconnector between Northern Ireland and Scotland to improve electricity interconnection within the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","49365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606015","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-24","<p>As a Government, we have been clear that we will do nothing to undermine workers’ rights. All law in this area at the time of exit will be brought under UK law as part of the Great Repeal Bill, ensuring continuity.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","49479","2016-10-24T09:47:23.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606015/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606015/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606015/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will take steps to ensure that the rights of part-time and agency workers will be (a) protected in the long-term and (b) retained in primary legislation.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","49396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606016","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-24","<p>As a Government, we have been clear that we will do nothing to undermine workers’ rights. The United Kingdom has one of the best records on occupational safety and health in Europe and the wider world and the Government intends to keep it that way. Health and safety regulations are secondary legislation under the Health and Safety at Work etc. Act 1974 and the Government has no plans to change this.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-24T11:44:33.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606016/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606016/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606016/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-19","Industrial Health and Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will take steps to ensure that all health and safety regulations will be (a) protected in the long-term and (b) retained in legislation after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","49395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606017","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Department for International Trade offers a wide range of business support. The Department provides International Trade Advisors across the UK, who give advice to companies wishing to start exporting or grow their exports. We also provide access to the wealth of information held by our overseas post network in over 100 locations in over 50 countries. Furthermore, the Department also offers a range of Digital Services including the Exporting is GREAT website, which I would encourage all British Businesses to visit.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-24T14:11:19.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606017/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606017/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606017/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-19","Exports: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what Government assistance has been offered to businesses to take advantage of the lower pound in exporting products.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","49318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606018","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-26","<p>The UK remains firmly committed to tackling global climate change. This commitment is enshrined in our domestic legislation via the Climate Change Act 2008. In line with this, we recently set the UK’s fifth domestic carbon budget in law. The UK remains a member of the European Union and existing rules apply.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-10-26T15:33:52.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606018/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606018/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606018/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Energy Companies Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his policy is on the Government maintaining its EU climate obligations after the UK leaves the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606019","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-25","<p>Most of the UK’s existing coal fired power stations are old, relatively inefficient and require investment to reduce the level of damaging pollutants they emit. I expect to consult shortly on the closure of unabated coal stations.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-25T13:05:01.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606019/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606019/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606019/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Coal Fired Power Stations: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, on what date he plans to open a consultation on the closure of coal plants by 2025.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","49432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606021","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-25","<p>Ministerial meetings with external organisations are published quarterly on the www.gov.uk website at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bis-quarterly-publications-april-to-june-2012" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bis-quarterly-publications-april-to-june-2012</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-10-25T14:14:03.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606021/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606021/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606021/answer","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606021/answer/previousversion/16138","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Nissan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether a Minister of his Department was present at the meeting between the Prime Minister and the Chief Executive of Nissan, Carlos Ghosn on 14 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","49465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606022","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-24","<p>As a Government, we have been clear that we will do nothing to undermine workers’ rights. All law in this area at the time of exit will be brought under UK law as part of the Great Repeal Bill, ensuring continuity.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","49396","2016-10-24T09:47:23.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606022/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606022/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606022/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Conditions of Employment: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will take steps to ensure that all EU-derived employment rights will be (a) protected in the long-term and (b) retained in primary legislation after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","49479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606023","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-27","<p>We are pleased that the Moyle interconnector is back up to full strength after a period of reduced capacity. This will help with security of supply, and the stability and flexibility of the grid in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>One of the issues for the Moyle interconnector is that imports into Scotland are constrained by wider constraints on the Scottish grid and on the border between Scotland and England. A number of measures are being taken to strengthen the Scottish grid and grid connections to England. These include the Western HVDC link, which is due for completion in mid-2017 and will provide an additional 2.2GW of capacity.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-27T16:48:10.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606023/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606023/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606023/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Electricity Interconnectors: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking fully to utilise the electricity interconnection between Northern Ireland and the rest of the UK before the UK leaves the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","49515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606025","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) has been formed after spending review 2015, out of the forerunner (non-ministerial) Departments UK Trade and Investment (UKTI) and the Trade Policy Unit responsibilities previously held by the Department for Business Innovation and Skills (BIS). My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade also has responsibility for UK Export Finance (the Export Credits Guarantee Department), which has its own budget.</p><p>The estimated annual budgeted operating costs of the department for the next four years are currently being established and will be submitted to parliament later this financial year.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-27T12:46:10.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606025/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606025/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606025/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-19","Department for International Trade: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how much funding his Department has been allocated for each fiscal year of the current Spending Review period.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606026","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-27","<p>The UK is a founding member of the WTO and will continue to have membership in its own right upon leaving the EU.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-10-27T13:27:32.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606026/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606026/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606026/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-19","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether it is the Government's policy to meet the requirements for automatically joining the World Trade Organisation on leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606027","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-27","<p>There are no civil servants that will receive severance pay or any other payments as part of their transfer to the Department for International Trade.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-10-27T15:02:53.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606027/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606027/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606027/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-19","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether any civil servants that transferred to his Department from other Government departments or public bodies received severance pay or other similar payments.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606028","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Government recognises the importance of ensuring regions and organisations have stability and certainty in the period leading up to our departure from the European Union. At the same time, we are keen to use the opportunities that departure presents to set our own priorities. The Chancellor has announced that the Treasury will guarantee structural fund bids which are signed before the UK leaves the EU. This includes funding for projects agreed after the Autumn Statement, if they represent good value for money, and if they are in line with the government’s strategic priorities, even if these projects continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU.</p><p>Leaving the EU means we will want to take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. Over the coming months, the government will consult closely with stakeholders to review all EU funding schemes in the round, to ensure that any ongoing funding commitments best serve the UK‘s national interest, while ensuring appropriate certainty.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-10-24T15:20:05.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606028/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606028/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606028/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Combined Authorities: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether funding currently received by mayoral combined authorities from EU structural funds will continue after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","49406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606029","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Government remains committed to making Britain the best place in Europe to start and grow a business. That includes supporting those businesses that trade with the EU and wider international markets, as well as continuing to encourage record foreign direct investment that supports business and communities up and down the country.</p><p>Over the coming weeks and months the Government will be engaging with businesses and key stakeholders up and down the country. We will listen to their concerns, aim to limit uncertainty in the transition and ensure our new relationship with the EU works for business.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-24T13:34:09.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606029/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606029/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606029/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Small Businesses: Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to ensure that the UK leaving the EU does not have a deleterious effect on the financial situation of small and medium-sized businesses; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606030","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-03","<p>UK-based researchers can continue to apply for competitive EU research funding through the Horizon 2020 programme while we remain a member of the EU. We will work with the Commission to ensure payment when funds are awarded. The Treasury will underwrite the payment of such awards, even when specific projects continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU. Access to apply to Horizon 2020 after we leave the EU will be a matter for the negotiations that will follow the triggering of Article 50.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-11-03T14:34:32.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606030/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606030/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606030/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Research: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether UK-based research institutions will be able to access the EU's Horizon 2020 programme until 2020; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606031","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-24","<p>​​The Department for Exiting the EU has engaged with a number of higher education institutions and groups including Universities UK and Royal Academies. Over the next few months the department will continue to engage with key stakeholders in business and civil society, including universities, through a series of roundtables, bi-laterals and visits across the UK.</p><p><br>We have been clear that we want to create an environment in which the UK as a whole can continue to be a world leader in research, science and the tertiary education sector more broadly. The government has already announced that UK researchers can still apply for Horizon 2020 projects and the Treasury will underwrite the payment of such awards, even when specific projects continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU. Equally, EU students applying for a place at an English university or further education institution in the 2017 to 2018 academic year will continue to be eligible for student loans and grants – and will be for the duration of their course.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","49427","2016-10-24T15:58:27.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606031/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606031/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606031/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Higher Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps he is taking to ensure that the UK leaving the EU does not have a deleterious effect on the operation of UK universities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606032","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-24","<p>​​The Department for Exiting the EU has engaged with a number of higher education institutions and groups including Universities UK and Royal Academies. Over the next few months the department will continue to engage with key stakeholders in business and civil society, including universities, through a series of roundtables, bi-laterals and visits across the UK.</p><p><br>We have been clear that we want to create an environment in which the UK as a whole can continue to be a world leader in research, science and the tertiary education sector more broadly. The government has already announced that UK researchers can still apply for Horizon 2020 projects and the Treasury will underwrite the payment of such awards, even when specific projects continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU. Equally, EU students applying for a place at an English university or further education institution in the 2017 to 2018 academic year will continue to be eligible for student loans and grants – and will be for the duration of their course.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","49429","2016-10-24T15:58:27.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606032/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606032/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Higher Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what representations he has received from universities on the effect of the UK leaving the EU on those institutions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606033","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-25","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the reply previously given on 25th October 2016, PQ UIN49488 by my hon Friend, the Minister of State for Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, George Eustice.</p><p>We recognise that the UK’s exit from the EU may have implications for the way in which current UK plant health services operate, including phytosanitary certification on imports, quarantine measures to mitigate the highest risk pests and diseases, and plant passporting.</p><p>We are considering the implications and possible options as part of our planning for, and negotiations on, the UK’s exit.</p><p>Continuing to deliver a risk-based, proportionate plant health regime that effectively protects the UK from plant pests and diseases, whilst maximising the free movement of goods, remains of the highest priority.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-25T15:04:59.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606033/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606033/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Quarantine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential implications of the UK leaving the EU for quarantine measures for pests and disease of plant material.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606034","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-26","Details of Ministers' meetings, gifts, hospitality and travel will be published on a quarterly basis as is standard practice.","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-26T16:12:10.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606034/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606034/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Department for Exiting the European Union: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 28 July 2016 to Question 43443, when his Department plans to publish its Quarterly Transparency Returns providing details of Ministerial meetings.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606035","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-25","<p>​O​fficials ​in my Department are not bound by any EU codes of conduct. This is true of Home Civil Service officials, Diplomatic Service officials, and locally engaged staff.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-25T14:40:05.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606035/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606035/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 20 September 2016 to Question 45844, how many of his Department's officials in Brussels are bound by EU codes of conduct which require them to act only with regard to the European Communities rather than a single member state.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606036","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-24","<p>Ministers and officials from across the Government are working closely with the Government of Japan and Japanese companies operating in the UK to reinforce the importance of a close relationship between our countries. They will continue to do so, including through our embassy in Tokyo.</p><p>The Department for Exiting the EU will continue to support this work.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-24T16:33:31.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606036/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606036/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Department for Exiting the European Union: Japan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2016 to Question 47489, whether, during the course of negotiations for the UK to leave the EU, his Department plans to hold discussions with its Japanese counterparts.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","49355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606037","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-25","<p>Detailed work is underway to establish the budget required to fulfil the department’s set-up and responsibilities, including staffing budget, over the period of the Spending Review. The budget will be presented to the House of Commons and approved as part of the supplementary estimates in the new year, as is standard practice.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","49501","2016-10-25T11:43:05.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606037/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606037/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Department for Exiting the European Union: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of the cost of (a) hiring and (b) transferring staff in his Department for each fiscal year of the Spending Review period.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606039","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-25","<p>Detailed work is underway to establish the budget required to fulfil the department’s set-up and responsibilities, including staffing budget, over the period of the Spending Review. The budget will be presented to the House of Commons and approved as part of the supplementary estimates in the new year, as is standard practice.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","49347","2016-10-25T11:43:05.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606039/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606039/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Department for Exiting the European Union: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how much funding his Department has been allocated for each fiscal year of the current Spending Review period.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606040","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-24","The implications of the Repeal Bill for devolved statute will require consultation and discussion with all the Devolved Administrations. The Prime Minister made the the offer today of a new official forum, to be chaired by Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, to the leaders of Scottish, Welsh and Northern Irish governments to allow them to help shape the UK's EU exit strategy.","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-24T16:35:22.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606040/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606040/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Devolution: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether powers not specifically reserved under Schedule 5 of the Scotland Act 1998 will automatically revert to the competence of the Scottish Parliament after the UK leaves the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","49524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606041","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-24","<p>We will not comment on the content of private Ministerial discussions. Details of Ministerial meetings will be published in the Department’s Quarterly Transparency Returns, which will be made publicly available on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>.</p><p>The Prime Minister set out her commitment to fully engage with the devolved administrations as the government delivers on the verdict of the UK people in their vote to leave the EU.</p><p>The Prime Minister said today at the Joint Ministerial Committee, that the government is ready to listen to proposals put forward by political leaders from Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland as she renegotiates the UK’s relationship with the EU.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-24T16:32:06.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606041/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606041/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Brexit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 17 October 2016 to Question 48004, if he will provide details of his discussions with the (a) First Minister of Scotland on developing a UK approach for the UK leaving the EU and (b) Minister for UK Negotiations on Scotland's place in Europe on the work of his Department.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","49559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606042","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has a dedicated legal team that is provided by the Government Legal Department. That team includes 28 qualified lawyers.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-10-24T15:53:20.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606042/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606042/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Department for Exiting the European Union: Legal Profession","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many legally trained staff are contracted to his Department for the purposes of their legal expertise; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606043","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-24","<p>As a new department we are currently in the process of migrating a large number of civil servants onto our HR systems from across government. As a result we do not hold this information.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-10-24T14:58:47.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606043/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606043/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606043/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Department for Exiting the European Union: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many civil servants working in his Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606045","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-25","<p>All Civil Servants working in the Department for Exiting the European Union continue to be employed as Civil Servants and therefore have not received severance payments or additional payments for joining the department.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-25T14:58:30.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606045/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606045/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Department for Exiting the European Union: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether any civil servants that transferred over to his Department received (a) severance pay and (b) other payments.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606046","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-25","Information about spend on hospitality for Senior officials, Ministers and Special Advisers will be published in the usual way through the transparency data on<a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank"> gov.uk</a>.<p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-10-25T11:35:53.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606046/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606046/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Department for Exiting the European Union: Official Hospitality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of his Department's spending on hospitality to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606189","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-01","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade’s CV is available on gov.uk.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-11-01T15:29:34.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606189/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606189/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-19","Liam Fox","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Price on 18 October (HL2097), whether they have assessed that the Secretary of State's curriculum vitae (CV) demonstrates experience of working inside British business; and if so, which part of that CV.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL2431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606190","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-26","<p>On 8 July 2016, the former Prime Minister (Rt Hon David Cameron MP) announced that following a recommendation by the Chief of the General Staff the previous exclusions on women serving in the Royal Marines (RM), Royal Armoured Corps (RAC), Infantry and Royal Air Force Regiment (RAF Regt) have now been lifted. This applies to both Regular and Reserve units.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) will initially open certain RAC units from November 2016, with all other Ground Close Combat roles opening from 2018. This will enable implementation to be rolled out in a deliberate, responsible and methodical manner that will allow mitigation measures, such as updated Physical Employment Standards, to be put in place.</p><p>Delivering the necessary organisational changes will be covered within current programmes and initiatives. Infrastructure changes across Defence will be achieved through existing development strategies and will not impact on the successful delivery of this policy change. The amount of funding required for longer term infrastructure solutions will be dependent on the number of women posted to particular establishments.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-10-26T15:08:49.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606190/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606190/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-19","Armed Forces: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Earl Howe on 22 February (HL6098), what progress they have made towards identifying and costing a long-term solution to the full integration of female soldiers in close combat roles in the Infantry and Royal Armoured Corps, the Royal Marines and the Royal Air Force Regiment.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL2432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606191","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-28","<p>The UK Government was influential in negotiating the new EU Package Travel Directive (2015/2302/EU). In particular the new rules extend protection to holidaymakers who pull together the elements of a package themselves using online providers, as well as those buying one “off the shelf”.</p><p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation including the updated Package Travel Directive.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-28T13:15:56.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606191/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606191/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Package Holidays: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the implications of the new EU Package Travel Directive (2015/2302/EU); and what plans they have to implement that Directive in advance of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Harris of Haringey",,"Lord Harris of Haringey","HL2433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606193","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising from the UK’s exit from the EU for our aviation industry. This includes the implications for UK-based airlines relating to Air Traffic Management and the Single European Sky after the UK leaves the EU.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-27T12:41:43.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606193/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606193/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","Air Traffic Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the implications for UK-based airlines of the Single European Sky when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Harris of Haringey",,"Lord Harris of Haringey","HL2434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606194","Home Office","false","2016-11-02","<p>The UK welcomes proposals to increase scrutiny of, and further secure, the EU’s external Schengen border. A brief update on the Commission’s plans to publish draft legislation for an Electronic Travel Information and Authorisation System was provided at the Justice and Home Affairs Council on 13 October, which was attended by the Home Secretary. We will examine the proposals in more detail once publication has taken place. The status of UK citizens under any such system will depend upon the nature of the detailed proposals and the outcome of the UK’s negotiations to exit the EU.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-02T16:03:42.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606194/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606194/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Borders: Personal Records","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of (1) the EU Commission proposal to introduce a European electronic system for travel authorisation (ESTA), and (2) the implications of the introduction of a European ESTA for UK citizens and businesses following the UK's departure from the EU; and what representations they have made to the Commission and to EU member states regarding that proposal.","false","Biography information for Lord Harris of Haringey",,"Lord Harris of Haringey","HL2435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606195","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-01","<p>Many social enterprises are charities, which are exempt from Corporation Tax on most income and gains if they are used for charitable purposes.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has also taken steps to support social enterprises by introducing the Social Investment Tax Relief (SITR). SITR provides tax relief to individuals when they invest in qualifying social enterprises.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has no plans to exempt all social enterprises from paying Corporation Tax, but keeps all tax policy under review.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-11-01T16:02:57.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606195/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606195/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-19","Corporation Tax: Social Enterprises","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have considered the merits of exempting social enterprises from paying corporation tax.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL2436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606196","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-31","​We remain concerned about reports of human rights abuses in Pakistan. Our concerns are reflected in the latest update to the Foreign and Commonwealth Office annual human rights report. We continue to urge Pakistan to honour in practice all its human rights obligations and uphold the rule of law. During his visit to Pakistan in March, the former Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), raised the importance we attach to safeguarding the rights of all Pakistani citizens regardless of ethnicity, faith or gender.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-31T14:46:34.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606196/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606196/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-19","Pakistan: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have made representations to the government of Pakistan concerning reports of human rights violations in that country.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL2437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606197","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-25","<p>Policy development for small modular reactors, including plans in respect of publishing a Roadmap, remains on-going. We are drawing on the findings of the independent Techno-Economic Assessment, the Phase One expressions of interest documents, the meetings held by officials over the summer with 32 technology vendors, service providers and potential investors, and our continuing discussions with regulators.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-25T11:28:17.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606197/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606197/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Nuclear Reactors","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are planning to publish a route map for the development of small modular nuclear reactors in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL2438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606198","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-31","<p>A clear majority of the UK electorate voted to leave the EU and we will respect the will of the people. The Government's position is that once given, our notification will not be withdrawn.</p><p>Our efforts will be focused on getting the best deal possible for the UK in the negotiations with the EU.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-10-31T17:20:13.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606198/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606198/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are planning to publish any legal advice they have received on whether or not the UK has the right to withdraw the Lisbon Treaty Article 50 notification before the two year time-limit has elapsed if negotiations to leave the EU under the provisions of Article 50 lead to unacceptable conditions for Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL2439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606199","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","HL2658","2016-11-01T13:13:29.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606199/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606199/answer","HL2440 & HL2658 Lord Wigley FINAL (1) (1).pdf","UKSA Response to HL2440 and HL2658","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606199/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-19","Dual Nationality: Republic of Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many UK citizens also have citizenship of the Republic of Ireland.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL2440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606200","Home Office","false","2016-11-15","<p>At present, the UK remains in the EU and there have been no immediate changes to the rights and obligations that membership entails. This means that EEA, Swiss and UK nationals continue to have the same rights and status that they had before the referendum.</p><p>The Prime Minister has been clear that a practical solution in the interests of all parts of the UK should be found to manage the border between Northern Ireland and Ireland once the UK has left the EU. Senior Officials from the UK, Ireland and Northern Ireland are working closely to consider the implications of the UK’s exit from the EU on the Common Travel Area (CTA). The CTA arrangement predates the EU and leaders in the UK and Ireland have been unequivocal –both want to maintain the current arrangement.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-15T17:58:02.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606200/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606200/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606200/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Immigration Controls: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what policy options they have considered regarding controls on EU citizens entering the UK through Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland following the UK's departure from the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL2441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606202","Department for Education","false","2016-10-28","<p>Primary and secondary schools can choose to teach the Welsh language to pupils if there is sufficient demand. It is possible for a pupil in England to take privately a Welsh language GCSE offered in Wales if an examination centre is willing to accept them. This will include a revised Welsh Second Language GCSE available for first teaching from September 2017.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-28T12:06:03.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606202/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606202/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-19","Welsh Language: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to make available the teaching of the Welsh language in schools in England.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL2442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606203","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-28","<p>There has been no further expenditure made by any other ministerial department into the Competition and Markets Authority inquiry regarding the overlap between Arriva buses and Arriva Trains.</p><p> </p><p>As an independent non-ministerial department, the CMA is responsible for merger inquiries. In this role, it has spent approximately £480k (including staff time, legal fees and consulting fees) investigating the acquisition of the Northern rail franchise by Arriva Rail North Ltd. It is not possible to establish what proportion of this figure was spent on the assessment of the overlap between Arriva Buses and Arriva Trains.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-28T12:33:59.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606203/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606203/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Northern Rail Franchise","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 19 October (HL2257), how much has been spent by departments other than the Department for Transport.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL2443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606204","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government intends to articulate in 2017 its emerging priorities for improvements to train services and the national rail network (including possible enhancements to the East Coast Main Line) from 2019.</p><p> </p><p>In Control Period 5 the Intercity Express Programme will provide the infrastructure to operate new trains from December 2018 which will reduce journey times and increase capacity. Schemes as part of the East Connectivity Fund will also be delivered to improve capacity and reduce journey times, the first of which is enhancements in the Doncaster area set to be complete by May 2017.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-27T12:42:23.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606204/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606204/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606204/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","East Coast Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the current capacity and reliability constraints on the East Coast Main Line railway will be comprehensively addressed in Control Period 6.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL2444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606205","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-02","<p>The responsibility for the management of off-road vehicles and motorcycles on public rights of way lies with local highway authorities and National Park Authorities, who have considerable powers to deal with problems of damage through the use of traffic regulation orders and also through the use of voluntary constraint agreements.</p><p> </p><p>No recent assessment of the state of the off-road network has been made, but previous research has shown that problems are localised.</p><p> </p><p>In order to share knowledge and build on existing best practice Defra and Natural England have set up a one-off forum for motor vehicle stakeholders in November to share their experiences and discuss ways of working together in the future.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-02T13:58:21.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606205/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606205/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606205/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-19","Rights of Way","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made in resolving problems of damage to rights of way caused by off-road vehicles and trail motorcycles.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL2445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606206","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-02","<p>This, like any other industrial dispute between a Train Operating Company and a trades union, is a matter for the union and operator to resolve. The Government condemns any industrial action that disrupts the travelling public. RMT has advised its members to accept the new On-Board Supervisor roles on offer. The Government’s strong opinion is there are no grounds at all for any further industrial action and these strikes must stop now.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-02T15:23:14.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606206/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606206/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606206/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","Southern: Industrial Disputes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to assist in the resolution of the industrial dispute between Southern Rail and some of its staff and their unions.","false","Biography information for Lord Condon",,"Lord Condon","HL2446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606207","Home Office","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Home Office fully supports the police exploiting technology to help cut crime wherever possible. Body worn video can be a powerful tool to help the police be more effective, efficient and accountable. The decision to procure and deploy it is an operational one for chief officers.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-02T15:52:47.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606207/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606207/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606207/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Police: Cameras","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to encourage the provision and wearing of body cameras by operational police officers to improve police and public confidence in cases of disputed incidents.","false","Biography information for Lord Condon",,"Lord Condon","HL2447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606208","Department for Education","false","2016-10-28","<p>The results of the consultation on implementing the English Baccalaureate and the Government’s response will be published in due course.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-28T12:06:18.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606208/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606208/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606208/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-19","English Baccalaureate","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will publish the results of their <i>Consultation on implementing the English Baccalaureate</i>, launched in November 2015.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL2448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606209","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-02","<p>We are committed to protecting our borders from pests and diseases and we are promoting biosecurity internationally, at UK borders, and inland.</p><p> </p><p>We are considering the implications for plant health biosecurity and possible options as part of our planning for, and negotiations on, the UK’s exit from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Continuing to deliver a risk-based, proportionate plant health regime, that effectively protects the UK from plant pests and diseases, whilst maximising the free movement of goods, remains one of the Government’s highest priorities.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-02T13:58:56.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606209/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606209/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606209/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-19","Plants: Imports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the UK exiting the EU, what steps they plan to take to tighten the rules governing the bio-security of imported trees and other plants.","false","Biography information for Lord Framlingham",,"Lord Framlingham","HL2449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606210","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-25","<p>We want the UK to be a country that works for everyone – and that includes those we intend to keep on helping through this programme. We are looking widely at all the evidence available to see how things could be done differently, to learn from it and see if there is even more we can do to improve the lives of troubled families. We will first consider the evidence of the first programme’s independent evaluation, but we are always open to learning from other programmes and reports.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-10-25T11:22:52.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606210/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606210/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606210/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-19","Disadvantaged: Children and Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will examine the results of the former Educational Priority Areas to explore whether similar measures could be combined with the continuing Troubled Families Programme<i>,</i> to improve results for disadvantaged children and young people.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606211","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>In the aftermath of the coup attempt we have emphasised the need for Turkey to respect human rights, including press freedom, and the rule of law. It is vital that the Turkish Government’s response to the coup attempt be demonstrably lawful and measured, and undertaken in line with Turkey’s international obligations. The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Rutland and Melton (Sir Alan Duncan) reiterated these messages to senior Turkish interlocutors, including President Erdogan, during his visit to Turkey on 19 October. We will continue to engage with the Turkish Government at all levels on these issues, and to monitor the situation closely.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-11-01T15:09:23.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606211/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606211/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606211/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-19","Turkey: Press Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the recent official closing in Turkey of more than 20 media outlets; and whether they will make representations to the government of Turkey about those closures.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606212","Home Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>As announced by the Home Secretary on Thursday 27th October the Child Trafficking Protection Fund is now open for bids and will make available up to £3m over three years to fund innovative projects to protect and support victims of child trafficking.</p><p>The Fund will enhance existing provisions to support these particularly vulnerable young people and will be open to both statutory and non-statutory organisations that work with potential victims. We encourage all interested organisations to put forward innovative proposals. More information can be found on the gov.uk contracts finder webpage.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-03T17:20:13.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606212/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606212/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606212/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Human Trafficking: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will publish full details of the Child Trafficking Protection Fund.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606213","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>There is no one body or individual that is specifically responsible for ensuring the Parades Commission complies with international treaty obligations, including on human rights. Further to my written answer of 17 October, the Commission operates independently of the Government, in line with the provisions contained in the Public Processions (NI) Act 1998. That Act is compliant with international treaty obligations on human rights, and the Commission is accountable to the courts for its operational decisions.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2016-10-31T10:50:35.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606213/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606213/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606213/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-19","Parades Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Dunlop on 17 October (HL2170), which body or individual ensures that the Northern Ireland Parades Commission is compliant with international treaty obligations concerning human rights.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL2453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606214","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>No revisions have been made to the procedural rules or the guidelines issued by the Parades Commission in the last five years. In line with the provisions of the Public Processions (NI) Act 1998, the procedural rules and the guidelines are required to be kept under review by the Commission; it is a matter for the Commission whether it proposes any revisions to the relevant instruments.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2016-10-31T10:50:52.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606214/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606214/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606214/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-19","Parades Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what revisions have been made to the Northern Ireland Parades Commission procedural rules and guidelines in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL2454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606215","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-25","<p>At the Spending Review 2015, £720 million was allocated to fund the remaining four years of the new Troubled Families Programme (2015 – 2020). We are absolutely committed to continuing to help this group of people, to help these vulnerable families that have some of the most complex needs of people in the country. We are looking at the evidence from the evaluation of the first Troubled Families Programme (2012-2015) to see how things could be done differently, to learn from it and see if there is even more we can do to improve the lives of troubled families.</p><p>We have already learnt lessons from the first Troubled Families Programme and reflected them in the design of the new programme. We have published an overview of the first programme (attached) which highlights the improvements that have been made: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-first-troubled-families-programme-2012-to-2015-an-overview" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-first-troubled-families-programme-2012-to-2015-an-overview</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-10-25T11:22:05.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606215/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606215/answer","161024 The first Troubled Families Programme an overview - HL2455.pdf","Troubled families programme - HL2455","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606215/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-19","Families: Disadvantaged","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to continue with the Troubled Families Programme in the light of the National Institute of Economics and Social Research's recent analysis.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606216","Home Office","false","2016-11-02","<p>The deployment of police officers to mental health settings and the tactics used are an operational matter for the police.</p><p>Any use of force by police officers must be appropriate, proportionate, necessary and conducted as safely as is possible. If police officers need to use force, it is right that they are expected to account for their actions.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-02T15:56:45.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606216/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606216/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Stun Guns","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether consideration is being given to prohibiting the use of tasers in detained settings for people with mental health conditions.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606217","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Government Buying Standard for food and catering was amended in October 2012 to state that, from the end of 2015, all palm oil used for cooking and as an ingredient in food shall be sustainably produced. The Government has been making good progress towards meeting this requirement, with the majority of departments reporting that their catering contractors are complying with it. The next report on progress under the Greening Government Commitments, covering 2015/16, will include an update on sustainable procurement issues, including palm oil.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-02T13:59:48.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606217/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606217/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-19","Palm Oil","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they have made on the implementation, through public procurement policy, of their commitment to achieve 100 per cent sourcing of credibly certified sustainable palm oil by the end of 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Parminter",,"Baroness Parminter","HL2457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606219","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Joint Statement on REDD+ by the United Kingdom, Germany and Norway made at the United Nations Climate Summit on 23 September 2014 in support of the New York Declaration on Forests contains a commitment that:</p><p> </p><p><em>“We will work with other consumer countries to promote national commitments that encourage deforestation-free supply chains, including through public procurement policies to sustainably source commodities such as palm oil, soy, beef and timber“.</em></p><p> </p><p>The Government Buying Standard for food and catering was amended in October 2012 to include a new requirement to procure palm oil, palm kernel oil and derivatives from sustainable sources. All food and catering products bought by central Government must meet these sustainability requirements.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s Timber Procurement Policy also requires central Government Departments, Executive Agencies and Non-Departmental Public Bodies to procure timber and timber products that are both legal and sustainable.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-02T14:00:43.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606219/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606219/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-19","Forests","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they have made, and when they plan to implement their commitment in the 2014 New York Declaration on Forests to work on new procurement policies to limit the consumption of commodities associated with deforestation.","false","Biography information for Baroness Parminter",,"Baroness Parminter","HL2458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606220","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-25","<p>Emissions of carbon dioxide from using biomass, including wood, in the energy sector are not reported within the national totals in the UK Greenhouse Gas Inventory because they are offset by the carbon dioxide absorbed by fast-growing bio-energy sources. The carbon stock they represent is reported in the land use change and forestry sector, in line with international guidelines set out by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC).</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-25T11:29:00.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606220/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606220/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-19","Timber","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what figure should be included for carbon dioxide emissions from wood, per unit of fuel, in the background data for fuel consumption used for the UK Greenhouse Gas Inventory 1990–2014, given that there is no figure for wood included in the table on the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs website.","false","Biography information for Baroness Parminter",,"Baroness Parminter","HL2459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606221","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-11-01","<p>Six European Court of Justice rulings have not yet been implemented. These are listed below:</p><p>1.Case number C-161/14 – Commission v UK</p><p>An infraction judgment made by the Court of Justice of the European Union, where the court ruled that the UK has failed to apply the VAT reduced rate to supplies of energy saving materials correctly. This is currently under review.</p><p>2. Case 301/10 (October 2012) – Urban Waste Water Treatment Directive – Commission v UK</p><p>The infraction judgment concerned the appropriate collection of urban waste water of agglomerations in Whitburn and London, and the appropriate treatment of urban waste water of agglomerations in London. Works on collection facilities at Whitburn are due to be completed by the end of 2017. Works to collection and treatment facilities, including the Thames Tideway Tunnel, are due to be completed by 2023.</p><p>3. Case 304/15 (September 2016) – Large Combustion Plants Directive – Commission v UK</p><p>The infraction judgment concerned permitted NOx emissions from a coal-fired power station in Aberthaw. The regulator, Natural Resources Wales, will review the environmental permit to amend the emission limits early in 2017, with modifications at the plant due to take place in summer 2017. There has also been a recalculation of the power station’s contribution to the UK’s Transitional National Plan for combustion plants.</p><p>4. C-530/11 European Commission v UK</p><p>The Court of Justice of the European Union handed down an infraction judgment concluding that the UK had breached EU law by failing to ensure procedures for certain environmental challenges were not prohibitively expensive.</p><p>5. Case number C-304/14 – Secretary of State for the Home Department v CS</p><p>A judgement on the interpretation of Article 20 TFEU, regarding the right of citizens of the Union and their family members to move and reside freely within the territory of the Member States.</p><p>6. Case number C-115/15 – Secretary of State for the Home Department v NA</p><p>A judgement on the interpretation of Articles 20 and 21 TFEU regarding freedom of movement for workers within the Community.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-11-01T17:04:05.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606221/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606221/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","European Court of Justice","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many European Court of Justice rulings against the UK government have not yet been implemented; and whether they will give details of those rulings.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL2460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606222","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government will comply with all the constitutional and legal obligations that apply to the deal that we will negotiate with the EU.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL2314","2016-10-27T10:57:11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606222/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606222/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-19","Brexit: Parliamentary Scrutiny","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to lay before Parliament for scrutiny the outcome of the negotiations for leaving the EU before those negotiations are concluded.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL2461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606223","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Department for International Development (DFID) share Project Literacy’s view that illiteracy leaves people around the world vulnerable to poverty, abuse and exploitation, and are committed to supporting the Global Goal target of ensuring that all youth and a substantial proportion of adults achieve literacy and numeracy by 2030. The majority of DFID’s education programmes are focused on ensuring all children are able to read, write and count. For example, DFID is helping to increase literacy rates amongst women and girls in Northern Nigeria, where 7 out of 10 women cannot read at all, through the Educating Nigerian Girls in New Enterprises project, which supports 18,000 young women to improve their literacy and numeracy.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-11-01T15:30:36.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606223/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606223/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606223/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-19","Literacy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the Project Literacy campaign, and whether they have plans to support and promote that campaign.","false","Biography information for Lord Bird",,"Lord Bird","HL2462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606224","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-31","<p>On average over the period 2010-2014, 40 per cent of the UK’s Official Development Assistance (ODA) was allocated to multilateral organisations. The table attached lists the top five multilateral organisations in terms of core funding.</p><p>Figures for 2015 will be published later this year.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-10-31T16:40:43.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606224/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606224/answer","HL2463 - Table.docx","PQ HL2463 - Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606224/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-19","International Assistance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proportion of the UK's international aid budget has been allocated to multilateral aid, and primarily through which institutions, in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Sandwich",,"The Earl of Sandwich","HL2463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606225","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-31","<p>As with bilateral aid, multilateral aid is subject to robust scrutiny by the International Development Committee and the Independent Commission on Aid Impact (ICAI). For example, ICAI published a review on “How the Department for International Development (DFID) works with multilateral agencies to achieve impact”, in June 2015 and the International Development Committee published an interim report on “UK Aid - Allocation of resources”, in March 2016.</p><p>The Secretary of State has clearly stated her commitment to driving higher results and ensuring value for money and transparency from DFID’s multilateral partners. DFID has taken a strategic approach to scrutinising the impact of our investment in multilateral organisations through the Multilateral Aid Review, the latest review is due to be published soon. The UK is also an active member of the Multilateral Organisation Performance Assessment Network (MOPAN), which brings together 18 donor countries with a common interest in assessing multilateral effectiveness. MOPAN will commission its own assessments of multilateral organisations.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-10-31T16:57:45.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606225/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606225/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-19","International Assistance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the scrutiny of the UK's bilateral aid programmes by the International Development Committee and the Independent Commission on Aid Impact, in addition to internal departmental audit and risk analysis, what level of scrutiny is applied to multilateral aid programmes.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Sandwich",,"The Earl of Sandwich","HL2464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606226","Home Office","false","2016-11-02","<p>We recognise e-cigarettes are an emerging technology and have taken action with the Chief Fire Officers’ Association, the then Department for Business, Innovation and Skills and with Electrical Safety First to develop appropriate fire safety messages for consumers.</p><p>These were promoted through the Fire Kills campaign, and continue to be made available on Electrical Safety First’s website - http://www.electricalsafetyfirst.org.uk/guides-and-advice/electrical-items/e-cigarettes/.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-02T15:56:06.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606226/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606226/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-19","Electronic Cigarettes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the fire risk posed by e-cigarettes and what discussion they have had with the LGA, London Councils and the leaders of Fire Authorities in England about this risk.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606227","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) and the Police are the bodies empowered to issue fixed penalty notices for commercial vehicle offences, including for breach of weight limits.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-02T15:19:39.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606227/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606227/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","Road Traffic Offences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to give local authorities the power to issue on the spot fines to commercial vehicles that disregard weight and other restrictions on the public highway.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606228","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Department for Transport discusses a wide range of issues with the RAC, AA and other motoring organisations with respect to highways maintenance and other issues that affect road users.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport is investing over £12 billion in this Parliament for highways maintenance. This comprises over £6 billion to local highway authorities in England, outside London, including £250 million between now and 2021 to help repair potholes and other defects.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-02T15:21:02.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606228/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606228/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606228/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the RAC, AA and other motoring organisations regarding the timely conduct of pothole repairs on roads in England.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606230","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-01","<p>Officials are continuing their work on implementing the Housing &amp; Planning Act 2016. A number of regulations have been implemented and this process will be on-going throughout 2017.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-11-01T15:43:28.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606230/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606230/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-19","Housing and Planning Act 2016","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will bring forward draft regulations under the Housing and Planning Act 2016.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606231","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Department for Transport works closely with the transport sector, including local highway authorities, to prepare for the winter season 2016/17.</p><p> </p><p>All key transport operators, including local authorities, train operating companies, Highways England, Network Rail and airports, have contingency plans in place to deal with winter weather that may be encountered.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport continues to liaise with salt producers and regularly updates the salt stock holdings being held across the country. The Government has retained an emergency salt stockpile of around 383,000 tonnes for this winter season. In addition both Highways England and local highways authorities have winter service vehicles for use on the road network, including 500 vehicles for dealing with incidents that may occur on the strategic road network.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport will shortly be writing to local highway authorities in England to remind them of their duties and to advise that they clean their drains and gullies in order to minimise the risk of surface water flooding on the highways for which they are responsible.</p><p> </p><p>It must, however, be recognised that severe winter weather may cause some disruption to the transport network. If travel is disrupted then we expect operators and highway authorities to do everything they can to keep passengers and road users informed whilst ensuring that the networks resume services as quickly as possible.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-02T15:20:38.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606231/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606231/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606231/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-19","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussion they have had with local authorities and the emergency services to ensure that roads in England and Wales are kept open in the event of poor winter weather in 2016–17.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606232","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-01","<p>Almhouses have for many hundreds of years played, and continue to play, an important role in providing homes for those in need in communities across the country.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-11-01T15:42:14.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606232/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606232/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606232/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-19","Almshouses","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the service provided by almshouses to local communities.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606233","Department for Education","false","2016-11-02","<p>Information on student support for students from England studying in the UK, and students from the EU studying in England, is published by the Student Loans Company (SLC) in the annual Statistical First Release Student Support for Higher Education in England (SFR). This can be found at: <a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx</a></p><p> </p><p>Provisional data included in the Supplementary Tables to the SFR shows that students studying at the Greenwich School of Management in 2014/15 received a total of £21 million in Tuition Fee Loan payments, £32.7 million in Maintenance Loans and £26.1 million in Grants (including Maintenance Grants and other grants such as the Disabled Students Allowance).</p><p> </p><p>Final data for the academic year 2014/15 and provisional data for the academic year 2015/16 will be published by the SLC on 30 November 2016.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","HL2472","2016-11-02T17:43:00.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606233/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606233/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606233/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-19","Greenwich School of Management","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the total amount of public money spent on maintenance fees individual students received by studying at the Greenwich School of Management in the academic years 2014–15 and 2015–16.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606234","Department for Education","false","2016-11-02","<p>Information on student support for students from England studying in the UK, and students from the EU studying in England, is published by the Student Loans Company (SLC) in the annual Statistical First Release Student Support for Higher Education in England (SFR). This can be found at: <a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx</a></p><p> </p><p>Provisional data included in the Supplementary Tables to the SFR shows that students studying at the Greenwich School of Management in 2014/15 received a total of £21 million in Tuition Fee Loan payments, £32.7 million in Maintenance Loans and £26.1 million in Grants (including Maintenance Grants and other grants such as the Disabled Students Allowance).</p><p> </p><p>Final data for the academic year 2014/15 and provisional data for the academic year 2015/16 will be published by the SLC on 30 November 2016.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","HL2471","2016-11-02T17:43:00.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606234/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606234/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606234/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-19","Greenwich School of Management","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much public money was spent on tuition fees in the form of bursaries for individuals studying at the Greenwich School of Management in the academic years 2014–15 and 2015–16.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606235","Department for Education","false","2016-11-02","<p>Information on the proportion of students attending examinations at Higher Education Providers is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Progression rates are not produced separately for those students receiving student support.</p><p> </p><p>Published statistics in respect of Alternatives Providers, including the Greenwich School of Management, are available in the Experimental Statistical First Release ‘Higher education student enrolments and qualifications obtained on undergraduate designated courses at alternative providers in England 2014/15’. This can be found at: <a href="https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/15-06-2016/sfr235-alternative-providers" target="_blank">https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/15-06-2016/sfr235-alternative-providers</a></p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","HL2474","2016-11-02T17:42:34.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606235/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606235/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606235/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-19","Greenwich School of Management","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of students in receipt of publicly-funded bursaries studying at the Greenwich School of Management for degrees validated by Plymouth University did not attend their examinations in the academic years 2014–15 and 2015–16.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606236","Department for Education","false","2016-11-02","<p>Information on the proportion of students attending examinations at Higher Education Providers is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Progression rates are not produced separately for those students receiving student support.</p><p> </p><p>Published statistics in respect of Alternatives Providers, including the Greenwich School of Management, are available in the Experimental Statistical First Release ‘Higher education student enrolments and qualifications obtained on undergraduate designated courses at alternative providers in England 2014/15’. This can be found at: <a href="https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/15-06-2016/sfr235-alternative-providers" target="_blank">https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/15-06-2016/sfr235-alternative-providers</a></p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","HL2473","2016-11-02T17:42:34.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606236/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606236/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606236/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-19","Greenwich School of Management","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the progression figures for students in receipt of publicly-funded bursaries studying at the Greenwich School of Management for degrees validated by Plymouth University for the academic years 2014–15 and 2015–16.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2474"
